@database main "MaxCID"
@node main "MaxCID by R. Smith"

MaxCID is a caller ID security door for MAXs BBS. It will take caller ID
information from a text file containing the formatted information (like
TrapDoor provides). e.g.

DATE = xxxx
TIME = xxxx
NMBR = xxx-xxx
NAME = xxxxxxx

It checks the information provided against the user's phone number in
the user database. If it is correct, all is well and it will exit. If
not, it will ask for the user's date of birth as a security check.

Should this fail, the user may be given a different access level, or can
be twitted. If this happens and the user's access level is reduced, they
will appear as having paged you.

A log file will be kept of incoming calls and security violations.

	@{"Installation" link inst}
	@{"Configuration" link conf}
	@{"Contact" link cont}
	@{"History" link hist}
	@{"Copyright" link copy}
@endnode
@node inst "Installing MaxCID"
To install MaxCID, you must first have a Doors: assign. Make a directory
called Doors:MaxCID and copy the executable and config file there.
Set it up to run automatically in IntroDoor.text (earlier the better).

Obviously, you will need a CallerID modem which provides a formatted output,
and also, the CLI signal itself. It works for me, but I'll improve the
program if you require (within reason :).

If you are updating, please see @{"Configuration" link conf}
@endnode
@node conf "Configuration for MaxCID"
The configuration is easy enough, just edit the file with a text editor.

The file itself has comments on the various lines which explain the
values.

As with MAXs BBS upon login, an access level of zero will twit the user.
Otherwise, the users access will be brought down to the level you set. It
will not affect users with a lower access level.

The text editor lines are fairly obvious. You can print a line of text or
a file. Just make sure you choose unused lines which won't clash with
another application.

If you have problems with that, look at the example config file provided,
or contact me.

@{B}UPDATE:@{UB} Comment lines are no longer used in MaxCID. Update will
copy all date comments to a new data file (SEE THE CONFIG FILE AGAIN).
It will only copy valid date comments, so running should produce an
accurate enough file. Just type "update".
@endnode
